The Chronicle Innocent Kurira, Sports Reporter
LADY Cheetahs coach Derek Chiwara has selected his squad for the Rugby Africa Women’s Sevens Cup in Jammel, Tunisia, this weekend. The tournament serves as a qualifier for the Sevens World Cup to be held in Cape Town, South Africa, from September 9-11 and the Commonwealth Games due to take place in Birmingham, England, from July 29. Zimbabwe are, however, not part of the Commonwealth. Winners of the competition will qualify for the Sevens World Cup. Bulawayo-based Robyn Mhembere is part of the squad that also includes Chiwoniso Mabika, Rumbidzai Chigumbu and Precious Marange. <img class="wp-image-604164 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-10-9.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-10-9.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-10-9-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Robyn Mhembere Speaking ahead of the competition,co-captain Margaret Magwaro said: “We have been preparing for the Africa Cup and it’s in a few days’ time.  <img class="size-full wp-image-604170" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-11-14.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-11-14.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-11-14-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> co-captain Margaret Magwaro So, yes, we have been preparing since last year. So, it’s been a long journey and we feel at this stage it is now the time to represent our country because we have worked for this and qualified and this is the time. “In the team we have a lot of young blood except for me obviously. So, we are confident that the young players will help us with their energy and I think this is the future of rugby if we look at the young ones.  We’re not only preparing for the Africa Cup actually, but foDerek Chiwarara  future tournaments. So as a team our goal is to come in the top four. We are hoping to come back with smiles if we get into the top four. Yes, we have been there before and we hope we can get back to where we were in previous years.” The games will be played tomorrow and Saturday, with nine countries, Senegal, Zimbabwe, Zambia, Uganda, Ghana, Kenya, Madagascar, South Africa and hosts Tunisia taking part. The Lady Cheetahs qualified for Tunisia after an impressive outing in the qualifiers held in Maseru, Lesotho, earlier this year. <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-604173" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-12-16.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-12-16.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-12-16-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The team finished the qualifiers unbeaten after convincingly winning all their four matches without conceding a point. Lady Cheetahs team Delight Mukomondo, Erika Mack, Caroline Malenga, Lindiwe Munerenyu, Chiwoniso Mabika, Rumbidzai Chigumbu, Precious Marange, Precious Chirinda, Samantha Chirongoma, Robyn Mhembere, Margaret Magwaro, Ropafadzo Madyah Management Head coach: Derek Kwayedza Chiwara Physiotherapist: Anne Butau Team manager: Vivienne Manuel -@innocentskizoe